  "prompt": "What are some things I should know about Brunei?",
  "response": "Brunei, officially known as the Nation of Brunei, the Abode of Peace, is a small but wealthy country located on the island of Borneo in Southeast Asia. Here are some key things to know about Brunei:\n\n### Geography and Climate\n- **Location**: Brunei is situated on the northern coast of Borneo, sharing borders with Malaysia and the South China Sea.\n- **Climate**: The country has a tropical rainforest climate with high humidity and temperatures ranging from 23\u00b0C to 32\u00b0C (73\u00b0F to 90\u00b0F) year-round.\n\n### Government and Politics\n- **Monarchy**: Brunei is an absolute monarchy ruled by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, who has been in power since 1967.\n- **Legal System**: The country follows a dual legal system of civil law based on English common law and Islamic Sharia law.\n\n### Economy\n- **Wealth**: Brunei is one of the wealthiest nations per capita due to its extensive petroleum and natural gas reserves.\n- **Currency**: The Brunei Dollar (BND) is the official currency, and it is pegged to the Singapore Dollar at a 1:1 ratio.\n\n### Culture and Society\n- **Religion**: Islam is the official religion, and the majority of the population is Muslim. The practice of other religions is allowed but generally less visible.\n- **Languages**: The official language is Malay, but English is widely spoken and used in business and education.\n- **Customs**: Bruneian culture is influenced by Malay traditions and Islamic values. Modesty and politeness are highly valued.\n\n### Attractions and Tourism\n- **Mosques**: The Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien Mosque and the Jame' Asr Hassanil Bolkiah Mosque are iconic landmarks.\n- **Rainforests**: Ulu Temburong National Park offers opportunities for ecotourism and exploring pristine rainforests.\n- **Water Villages**: Kampong Ayer, the water village in the capital Bandar Seri Begawan, provides a glimpse into traditional Bruneian life.\n\n### Education and Healthcare\n- **Education**: Education is highly prioritized, with free schooling up to the university level for citizens.\n- **Healthcare**: Brunei offers free healthcare services to its residents, with modern facilities and comprehensive services.\n\n### Miscellaneous\n- **Population**: Brunei has a small population of around 465,000 people.\n- **Transportation**: The country has a limited public transportation system, but it is easy to navigate with taxis and private vehicles.\n- **Safety**: Brunei is considered one of the safest countries in the world with a low crime rate.\n\nUnderstanding these aspects of Brunei can help provide a well-rounded view of this unique and prosperous nation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
